00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:22.160
So now, and I'm going to talk to
you about the origins of this,

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:26.360
many, many infectious
agents that we thought we

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:27.680
had conquered--

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:29.180
we thought we could
take care of it.

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:33.004
You just take this course of
antibiotics and you're off,

00:08:33.004 --> 00:08:34.100
you're set.

00:08:34.100 --> 00:08:37.880
But now, because of the
rapid mutation rates

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:41.570
in bacteria and viruses,
certain pathogens

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:44.420
have completely
worked out mechanisms

00:08:44.420 --> 00:08:46.520
to escape therapeutic agent.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:48.680
And I'm going to talk to
you about those mechanisms

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:50.690
towards the end of this class.

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:53.780
So basically you can
dose a person one day

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:56.750
with a normal dose of
an antibiotic agent,

00:08:56.750 --> 00:09:00.620
and then 10 months later
that normal dose or 10 times

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:03.740
or 100 times that
dose stops working.

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:04.940
Why is that?

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:08.870
It's due to resistance
acquisition due to rapid cell

00:09:08.870 --> 00:09:14.360
division and mistakes made on
replication and transcription,

00:09:14.360 --> 00:09:17.150
that then may one
in a million times

00:09:17.150 --> 00:09:20.510
confer an advantage
on the microorganism.

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:24.610
All of a sudden the
drugs don't work anymore.

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:30.530
The WHO and various
community notice boards

00:09:30.530 --> 00:09:35.320
call this set of infectious
agents the escape pathogens.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.790
It helps us remember
which ones these are,

00:09:37.790 --> 00:09:41.480
because these are pathogens
that escape treatment,

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:43.880
because they've
developed resistance

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:46.310
to multiple drug cocktails.

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:49.550
So commonly, when someone
has a particular disease

00:09:49.550 --> 00:09:52.460
they don't take one drug,
they take two or three

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:56.210
to hit lots of pathways
at once in the hope

00:09:56.210 --> 00:09:58.610
that resistance
won't develop fast.

00:09:58.610 --> 00:10:01.820
But the escape pathogens
have collectively

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:04.910
acquired resistance to
several antibiotics,

00:10:04.910 --> 00:10:07.460
meaning there's
no good treatment.

00:10:07.460 --> 00:10:12.440
So the letters of escape stand
for Enterococcus faecium,

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:17.030
Staph aureus, Klebsiella
pneumoniae, Acinetobacter

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:20.210
baumannii, Pseudomonas
aeruginosa, and some

00:10:20.210 --> 00:10:23.090
of the Enterobacter species.

00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:30.210
Some of these infectious
agents are what result from--

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:32.550
I always say this wrong--

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.560
nosocomial infections.

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:37.680
Does anyone know what those are?

00:10:37.680 --> 00:10:41.450
These are infections that
people get in hospitals.

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:44.280
So Tom Brady had
a knee operation.

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:47.730
He got an infection in his knee
that came from the surgery,

00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:48.330
right.

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:50.970
These are hospital
acquired infections,

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:56.370
because you can't sometimes
clear an area enough,

00:10:56.370 --> 00:10:58.710
and there's infectious
agents around.

00:10:58.710 --> 00:11:03.240
So Acinetobacter baumannii
was dubbed the Iraqi Bug

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:07.200
for many, many years, because
the vets coming back from Iraq

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:10.080
were going to
military hospitals,

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:13.230
and these were
abundant with cases

00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:15.390
of Acinetobacter baumannii.

00:11:15.390 --> 00:11:18.900
So that moved on to the
escape pathogen list.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:21.090
So these are things
to watch out for.

00:11:21.090 --> 00:11:23.880
It's the reason that
nosocomial infections--

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:25.590
I hope I'm saying
it right, otherwise

00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:28.260
