infections, because bacteria

00:14:50.670 --> 00:14:54.450
tend to cloak themselves
with unusual sugar

00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:56.850
polymers and other
kinds of structures

00:14:56.850 --> 00:14:58.980
that the body doesn't
really know what to do with.

00:14:58.980 --> 00:15:01.500
And in some cases
they kind of mimic

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:03.780
things that are
in the human body.

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:07.920
So they they are mimetics
of normal structures

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:09.330
in the human body.

00:15:09.330 --> 00:15:12.210
And the body just doesn't
notice them at all.

00:15:12.210 --> 00:15:15.300
And then there are
incidences where

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:18.420
certain bacterial
infections later on

00:15:18.420 --> 00:15:20.830
cause autoimmune disease.

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:22.650
So a bacteria may come along.

00:15:22.650 --> 00:15:25.680
It may have something that looks
kind of like something human,

00:15:25.680 --> 00:15:27.240
but not quite.

00:15:27.240 --> 00:15:30.150
The human body responds,
develops antibodies,

00:15:30.150 --> 00:15:35.220
and then they cross talk back
to aspects of our physiology.

00:15:35.220 --> 00:15:39.260
So Campylobacter jejuni is
often a contaminant in poultry.

00:15:39.260 --> 00:15:41.240
It's a severe GI infection.

00:15:41.240 --> 00:15:44.690
But later on people get
diseases such as Guillain-Barre,

00:15:44.690 --> 00:15:49.790
which is a neuropathy where
the ends of your limbs

00:15:49.790 --> 00:15:52.310
become numb and non-functional.

00:15:52.310 --> 00:15:55.250
So there was a famous
football player,

00:15:55.250 --> 00:15:57.110
the one they called
"The Refrigerator," who

00:15:57.110 --> 00:16:01.160
had a serious case of
Guillain-Barre resulting

00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:04.070
from very much an
infectious disease, which

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:07.810
converted into autoimmunity.

00:16:07.810 --> 00:16:10.660
So let's now look at
antibiotic targets.

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:13.510
And to look at
antibiotic targets,

00:16:13.510 --> 00:16:16.300
I think the first
clear place to look

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:18.610
is at the bacterial cell wall.

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:32.090
Now when we first started
talking about prokaryotes,

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:36.260
things that include bacteria,
we talked about the fact

00:16:36.260 --> 00:16:38.690
that these single
celled organisms

00:16:38.690 --> 00:16:44.270
have to have a robust cell
wall to prevent osmotic shock.

00:16:44.270 --> 00:16:45.770
They have to have
some kind of thing

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:49.730
to keep them from
taking up too much water

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:53.420
and basically exploding
because of osmosis.

00:16:53.420 --> 00:16:57.530
Water floods in to balance
the salt concentrations.

00:16:57.530 --> 00:17:01.260
So they have a
complex cell wall,

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:09.500
which is made of a macro
molecule called peptidoglycan

00:17:09.500 --> 00:17:12.650
And it's usually one word,
but I want to just underline

00:17:12.650 --> 00:17:16.940
peptidoglycan because it's
a fascinating polymer that's

00:17:16.940 --> 00:17:21.575
made up of peptides and
linear carbohydrate polymers.

00:17:22.290 --> 00:17:25.190
So if you look at this
typical bacterium,

00:17:25.190 --> 00:17:29.910
this is just a cartoon
of the peptidoglycan.

00:17:29.910 --> 00:17:38.210
So it's a cross-linked
polymer, we

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:43.250
in one direction it has
repeating carbohydrate units.

00:17:43.250 --> 00:17:46.910
I'm not drawing those complex
hexose structures there.

00:17:46.910 --> 00:17:49.250
I'm just drawing
it in cartoon form.

00:17:49.250 --> 00:17:53.755
And those are carbohydrates
known as NAG and NAN.

00:17:57.890 --> 00:18:03.140
NAG is N-Acetyl Glucosamine.

00:18:03.140 --> 00:18:04.850
It's a hexose sugar.

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:07.420
NAN is N-AcetylMuramic acid.

00:18:07.420 --> 00:18:09.890
It's another modified sugar.

00:18:09.890 --> 00:18:12.010
And on the one of
those sugars, there

00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:19.190
is a reactive site that allows
you to basically cross-link

00:18:19.190 --> 00:18:21.830
these polymers into a mesh work.

00:18:21.830 --> 00:18:26.150
So it's a feat of engineering
to build this amazing polymer.

00:18:26.150 --> 00:18:29.870
It starts being built on the
inside, on the cytoplasm.

00:18:29.870 --> 00:18:32.960
And then the components get
flipped onto the other side

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:35.660
of the cytoplasm of bacteria.

00:18:35.660 --> 00:18:38.120
Then they get
polymerized in place

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:41.780
to make this complex
mesh work of a polymer

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:46.190
that creates the rigidity
of the bacterial cell wall.

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:50.270
It's generically known
as a peptidoglycan.

00:18:50.270 --> 00:18:53.720
Different bacteria have
different peptidoglycans.

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:56.240
There are several
modifications that

00:18:56.240 --> 00:19:01.430
might be specific to
particular bacterial sera

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:03.110
But this is the
generic structure,

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:05.600
where you have a polymer
that's built of sugars.

00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:07.910
You can recognize the
sugar structure there

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:11.690
going in one direction and
the peptide component that

00:19:11.690 --> 00:19:15.350
cross-links across in
order to make this mesh.

00:19:15.350 --> 00:19:18.350
And bacterial wall have
different amounts of this,

00:19:18.350 --> 00:19:21.770
but it'll build up to a
really strong, rigid mesh

00:19:21.770 --> 00:19:25.370
work that's permeable to things,
small molecules and water.

00:19:25.370 --> 00:19:26.960
There is holes, and so on.

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:29.600
But it creates a
mechanical rigidity

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:33.110
so that osmotic shock doesn't
occur on the bacteria.

00:19:33.110 --> 00:19:34.160
Any questions about that?

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:35.230
Does that makes sense?

00:19:35.230 --> 00:19:38.060
So that, in a sense,
it's their exoskeleton,

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:40.670
if you want to think
about it like that.

00:19:40.670 --> 00:19:43.610
So the properties are rigid.

00:19:43.610 --> 00:19:46.610
Without it, the bacteria
would suffer osmotic shock.

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:52.160
And it's plenty permeable
to allow 2-nanometer type

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:57.048
pores in order for nutrients and
water to go into the structure.

